<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>Should You Outsource Your Morning Routine to a Chatbot?</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/magazine/ai-chatbot-morning-routine-videos.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/magazine/ai-chatbot-morning-routine-videos.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/04/magazine/ai-chatbot-morning-routine-videos.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A.I. wants to help you start the day. Its suggestions? Drink coffee and get dressed.</description><dc:creator>Sophie Haigney</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 04 Jun 2026 09:03:39 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Habits and Routines</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">TikTok</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/14/magazine/14mag-screenland/14mag-screenland-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Aniyah Uniquee/@Aniyahuniquee</media:credit></media:content></item><item><title>Larry Sanger, a Wikipedia Founder, Is Barred From Editing on the Site</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/business/media/wikipedia-larry-sanger-barred.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/business/media/wikipedia-larry-sanger-barred.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/business/media/wikipedia-larry-sanger-barred.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A vote to bar Larry Sanger indefinitely from the volunteer community of Wikipedia came days after he submitted a proposal on “intellectual diversity.”</description><dc:creator>Adeel Hassan</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2026 11:48:07 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Larry Sanger</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Wikipedia</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">internal-eafs</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/24/multimedia/24xp-wikipedia/24xp-wikipedia-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Ulli Winkler/ullstein bild, via Getty Images</media:credit><media:description>Larry Sanger said that Wikipedia was “one of the most effective organs of establishment propaganda in history.”</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>OpenAI Leans Toward Holding Up I.P.O. Until Next Year</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/openai-ipo-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/openai-ipo-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/openai-ipo-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The A.I. company’s advisers are pushing its chief executive, Sam Altman, to move slowly after SpaceX’s stock has been volatile and as the start-up grapples with financial challenges.</description><dc:creator>Rob Copeland and Mike Isaac</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2026 20:31:22 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">IPO</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">SpaceX</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sam Altman</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sarah Friar</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/25/multimedia/25biz-openai-ipo-sam-flvk/25biz-openai-ipo-sam-flvk-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Haiyun Jiang/The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Sam Altman, the chief executive of OpenAI, has pushed for a trillion-dollar I.P.O.</media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>